{
  "discovery": {
    "context": "`Morgen` means \"tomorrow,\" `Heute` means \"today,\" and `Jetzt` means \"now.\"",
    "options": [
      {
        "feedback": "Exactly right! In every example, the verb occupies the second position in the sentence — whether the sentence starts with a subject, a time expression, or another element. This is German's verb-second (V2) rule.",
        "isCorrect": true,
        "text": "The verb always comes second, regardless of what word starts the sentence"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Not quite. Look at the first example: 'Ich spiele Tennis' — the subject 'Ich' comes first. In the other examples, the verb still comes second, but a different element takes the first position.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "The subject always comes first in German sentences"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "That's true of these examples, but it's a coincidence of the content chosen — not the grammar pattern. Focus on WHERE the verb appears in each sentence relative to the other elements.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "All the sentences are about daily activities"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Close, but not quite the full picture. The verb's position doesn't depend on the subject — it depends on what comes before it. Notice that when something other than the subject starts the sentence, the subject and verb swap positions.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "The verb always comes right after the subject"
      }
    ],
    "question": "Look at the highlighted verbs. What pattern do you notice about where they appear in each sentence?"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "highlight": "spiele",
      "romanization": null,
      "sentence": "Ich spiele Tennis.",
      "translation": "I play tennis."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "spiele ich",
      "romanization": null,
      "sentence": "Morgen spiele ich Tennis.",
      "translation": "Tomorrow I play tennis."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "lernt",
      "romanization": null,
      "sentence": "Sie lernt Deutsch.",
      "translation": "She learns German."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "lernt sie",
